{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f3fc3678-0887-4c0a-98c2-72ca41143991","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. You can find it in:\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — per-user crash logs\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-wide crash logs\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n### Getting a core dump instead\n\nIf you need a full core dump (for lldb/dotnet-dump analysis):\n\n```bash\n# Allow core dumps\nulimit -c unlimited\n# macOS writes cores to /cores/ by default\nls /cores/\n```\n\nRe-run the app after setting `ulimit` and you'll get a `/cores/core.<pid>` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f851d2aa-4f6e-44fe-ba08-0ce5b2133f75","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question - no tools needed.","outputTokens":274},"id":"1a44352a-f791-43af-9ea1-bf22d1f8273e","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:01:02.451Z","parentId":"aa235aab-4358-46f2-b0eb-08269de3fbb4"}
